{"title_page": "Krishnarao Phulambrikar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Krishnarao Phulambrikar\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = 20 January 1898\n| birth_place        = [[Alandi|Devachi Alandi]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n| death_date         = {{Death date|df=yes|1974|10|20}}\n| death_place        = Pune\n| restingplace       = \n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| othername          = Master Krishnarao, Master Krishna\n| occupation         = Classical musician<br>Vocalist, Film and Drama artist\n| yearsactive        = \n| known for          = [[Hindustani music]]<br>[[Marathi Sangeet Natak]]<br>[[Marathi and Hindi cinema|Marathi and Hindi film]] music\n| spouse             = Radhabai Phulambrikar\n| domesticpartner    = \n| children           = Madhav alias Raja Phulambrikar, Veena Chitko and Anupama Subhedar\n| parents            = Ganesh Phulambrikar<br>Mathura\n| website            = \n| signature          = \n| awards             = [[Padma Bhushan]]<br>[[List of Sangeet Natak Akademi fellows|Sangeet Natak Akademi Fellowship]]<br>Vishnudas Bhave Gold Medal\n}}\n'''Krishnarao Ganesh Phulambrikar''' (1898\u20131974), popularly known as '''Master Krishnarao''', was an Indian vocalist, classical musician and composer of [[Hindustani music]].<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar\">{{cite web | url=http://www.parrikar.org/vpl/?page_id=672 | title=Krishnarao Phulambrikar | publisher=Vijaya Parrikar Library | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> He was credited with the creation of three Hindustani [[ragas]] and several [[bandish]]es. Phulambrikar, a recipient of the [[List of Sangeet Natak Akademi fellows|Sangeet Natak Akademi Fellowship]],<ref name=\"Sangeet Natak Akademi Fellowship\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/Fellows.html | title=Sangeet Natak Akademi Fellowship | publisher=Sangeet Natak Akademi | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727131515/http://www.sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/Fellows.html | archive-date=27 July 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref> was also the music composer of several movies, including [[Dharmatma (1935 film)|Dharmatma]], a 1935 Hindi film starring [[Bal Gandharva]], a renowned [[Marathi cinema|Marathi]] singer<ref name=\"Dharmatma on IMDb\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0267425/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm | title=Dharmatma on IMDb | publisher=IMDb | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> and [[Padosi (film)|Padosi]], a 1941 directorial venture of [[V. Shantaram]].<ref name=\"Padosi on IMDb\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0331308/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm | title=Padosi on IMDb | publisher=IMDb | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> The Government of India awarded him the third highest civilian honour of the [[Padma Bhushan]], in 1971, for his contributions to music.<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2016 |accessdate=3 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nKrishnarao Phulambrikar was born in 1898 at [[Alandi|Devachi Alandi]], a town in the periphery of [[Pune]], in the western Indian state of [[Maharashtra]] to the [[Deshastha Brahmin]] couple Ganesh Phulambrikar and Mathura bai.<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\">{{cite web | url=https://www.swarganga.org/artist_details.php?id=108 | title=Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas' | publisher=Swar Ganga Music Foundation | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> He also ventured into [[Marathi theatre]] as a child artist by performing as an actor-singer in ''Sant Sakhu'', a musical drama produced by ''Natyakalapravartak Mandali''. He also acted in other musical dramas produced by this drama company. And at this drama company, he first got a chance to learn Indian classical music from Sawai Gandharva who used to act in the musical dramas of this company. Later, he approached the renowned singer, [[Bhaskarbuwa Bakhale]] in 1911 who trained the young boy in [[Gwalior gharana|Gwalior]], [[Agra gharana|Agra]] and [[Jaipur Gharana Lineage|Jaipur]] [[gharanas]] of [[Hindustani music]] and their guru-shishya relationship lasted till Bakhale's death in 1922.<ref name=\"Deodhar1993\">{{cite book|author=B. R. Deodhar|title=Pillars of Hindustani music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cAkUAQAAIAAJ|date=1 October 1993|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7154-555-1}}</ref> The tutelage under Bakhale also gave him opportunity to meet and get associated with [[Bal Gandharva]], who would later go on to become a noted [[Marathi cinema|Marathi singer]].<ref name=\"1898 \u2013 1974 Master Krishnaji Prabhakar Khadilkar\">{{cite web | url=https://fb1site.wordpress.com/2015/11/23/1898-1974-master-krishnaji-prabhakar-khadilkar/ | title=1898 \u2013 1974 Master Krishnaji Prabhakar Khadilkar | publisher=FB1 | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> His first solo concert was when he was 14 years of age (he was awarded the title of ''Sangeet Kalanidhi'' in 1933 by Shankaracharya), which preceded several concerts in India and abroad, including a trip to China as a Government of India delegate in 1953.<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" />\n\nPhulambrikar served as the director of ''Pune Bharat Gayan Samaj'', a music academy founded by his mentor [[Bhaskarbuwa Bakhale]] in Pune.<ref name=\"The Pillars & Mentors\">{{cite web | url=http://www.punebharatgayansamaj.org/history.html | title=The Pillars & Mentors | publisher=Pune Bharat Gayan Samaj | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> Besides his career as a classical vocalist and as a film music composer, he scored music for several plays which included ''Menaka'', ''Savitri'', \"Asha Nirasha\", ''Amritasidhhi'', ''Kanhopatra'', ''Nand Kumar'' and ''Vidhi Likhit'' for ''Gandharva Sangeet Natak Mandali'', a drama company founded by [[Bal Gandharva]], during the period 1915\u20131933 and acted in a few of them. Later, he also composed music for a few plays such as ''Kulavadhu'', ''Ek Hota Mhatara'', ''Kone Eke Kali'' and ''Bhagyoday'' for [[Jyotsna Bhole]].<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" /> On the academic front, he compiled the compositions taught to him by Bakhale as well as his own compositions and published them as a 7-volume book, ''Raag Samgraha''.<ref name=\"Books on Indian Classical Music\">{{cite web | url=https://www.swarganga.org/books.php | title=Books on Indian Classical Music | publisher=Swar Ganga Music Foundation | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Master Krishnarao (1897- )\">{{cite web | url=http://www.moutal.eu/audio-archives/vocal/h-m/289-master-krishnarao-1897-.html | title=Master Krishnarao (1897- ) | publisher=Moutal | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> Besides his notations are available in print under the titles, ''Rashtra Sangeet'', ''Shishu Sangeet'', ''Amar Sangeet'', ''Mohan Maal'', ''Natya Geet Notations'' and ''Chitra Geet Notations''. He also tutored several musicians, film and drama artists. [[Ram Marathe]], Yogini Joglekar, Saraswati Rane, Haribhau Deshpande, Anjanibai Kalgutkar, Madhusudan Kanetkar, Jaymala Shiledar, Dr.Pabalkar, Bapurao Ashtekar, Dattopant Bhope, Pitre buwa, Suhas Datar, Sudhakar Joshi, Ravindra Joshi, Mohan Karve, Rangnath Karkare, Shivram Gadgil and his daughter, Veena Chitko are some of his notable disciples.<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" />\n\n== Hindustani music career ==\nPhulambrikar was known to have had expertise in [[khayal]] and [[Thumri]] traditions of classical music rendition and was aligned to the [[Agra gharana]].<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" /> He created several [[ragas]] by merging the nuances of different ragas; thus he created ''Tilak Kedar'' based on Tilak Kamod and Kedar ragas, Mangal Todi on [[Todi (raga)|Todi]] and Madhyam, Shiva Kalyan on [[Kalyani (raga)|Kalyan]] and [[Shivaranjani]], Bilvabibhas on [[Bilaval]] and [[Bibhas]] and Jaunkali based on [[Jaunpuri (raga)|Jaunpuri]] and [[Ramkali]] ragas. He was reported to have initiated the practice of creating new Natyapadas<ref name=\"Agra gharana & areas of Impact\">{{cite web | url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/56174/12/12_chapter%205.pdf | title=Agra gharana & areas of Impact | publisher=Shodh Ganga | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> and composed many [[bandish]]es such as ''Ratiya Mein Jagi'' ([[Kanada (raga group)|Rag Nayaki Kanada]]), ''Lalan Tumabina Kaun'' ([[Kanada (raga group)|Rag Kaunsi Kanada]]), ''Rang Rang Mukhape'' ([[Adana (raga)|Rag Adana]]), ''Chahu Barasan Lagi'' ([[Bhopali|Rag Bhopali]]), ''Kahu Ki Reet'' ([[Malkaush|Rag Malkaush]]), ''Hori Khela! Bahar'' ([[Patdeep|Rag Patdeep]]), ''E Ma Badal Aye'' ([[Malhar|Rag Malhar]]), Mai Ri Aaj ([[Hindol|Rag Hindol Bahar]]), Mai Pritam Karo Dulhan Pe ([[Kalyani (raga)|Rag Shiv Kalyan]]).<ref name=\"The raags of the Ganesh pandals: The magic of Master Krishnarao\">{{cite web | url=http://scroll.in/article/755954/the-raags-of-the-ganesh-pandals-the-magic-of-master-krishnarao | title=The raags of the Ganesh pandals: The magic of Master Krishnarao | publisher=Scroll.in | date=19 September 2015 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> ''Tori Binati'', ''Dekho Mori Churiya'', ''Shamamohan Pyare'', ''Khelat Hai Giridhari'', ''Ho Sham Bajayetore Gharame Muraliya'', all in [[Bhairavi (raga)|Rag Bhairavi]], were some of his notable thumris in Bhairavi, earning him the sobriquet, ''Bhairavi ke Badshah'' and the style he developed came to be known as ''Khayali Thumri'' or ''Madhyamgram Thumri''.<ref name=\"Regional Varieties of Thumri\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nadsadhna.com/Pages/IndianMusic/Gharanas.asp?About=Baneras | title=Regional Varieties of Thumri | publisher=Nad Sadhna | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> He tuned the Indian national song, [[Vande Mataram]],  in ''Raag Jhinjhoti'' and tried unsuccessfully to promote the song as the [[National Anthem of India|national anthem]].<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" /> On special request made by Dr.Babasaheb Ambedkar, he composed music for Buddha Vandana.\n\n== Film career ==\nSoon after he received the Sangeet Kalanidhi title from Dr. Kurtkoti, the Shankaracharya of Karvir Peeth, he was contracted by [[Prabhat Film Company]]<ref name=\"The Talkie Era \">{{cite web | url=https://www.cs.colostate.edu/~malaiya/music_hist.html | title=The Talkie Era | publisher=Colostate | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> owned by [[V. Shantaram]] and other partners,<ref name=\"GokulsingDissanayake2013\">{{cite book|author1=K. Moti Gokulsing|author2=Wimal Dissanayake|title=Routledge Handbook of Indian Cinemas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=djUFmlFbzFkC&pg=PA259|date=17 April 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-77284-9|pages=259\u2013}}</ref> to compose music for its forthcoming film, [[Dharmatma (1935 film)|Dharmatma]], where he was re-united with his old associate, [[Bal Gandharva]], who played the role of [[Sant Eknath]], the protagonist of the movie.<ref name=\"Full Cast & Crew\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0267425/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm | title=Full Cast & Crew | publisher=IMDb | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> The film which was released in 1935 had sixteen songs, many of them sung by Bal Gandharva.<ref name=\"Dharmatma Songs\">{{cite web | url=http://muvyz.com/moviepage/es289902/songs/#tabs | title=Dharmatma Songs | publisher=Muvyz | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> A year later, his next film was released under the name, [[Amar Jyoti]], again a Prabhat Film Company production.<ref name=\"Amar Jyoti (1936)\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0268915/?ref_=nm_flmg_com_7 | title=Amar Jyoti (1936) | publisher=IMDb | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> The film was reported to have been critically acclaimed and was the first Indian film to be screened at the [[Venice Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Rishi2012\">{{cite book|author=Tilak Rishi|title=Bless You Bollywood!: A Tribute to Hindi Cinema on Completing 100 Years|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r623sWyGm0sC&pg=PA155|year=2012|publisher=Trafford Publishing|isbn=978-1-4669-3963-9|pages=155\u2013}}</ref> ''Wahan'', another Prabhat production released in 1937, this time with a new director, K. Narayan Kale, was his next film,<ref name=\"Wahan (1937)\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0232919/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm | title=Wahan (1937) | publisher=IMDb | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> followed by the musical [[Gopal Krishna (1938 film)|Gopal Krishna]] in 1938 directed by Damle and S Fattelal.<ref name=\"Gopal Krishna (1938)\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0158642/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm | title=Gopal Krishna (1938) | publisher=IMDb | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> He composed music for 15 films which included [[Padosi (film)|Padosi]], another Shantaram film and the film featured a ten-minute song, ''Lakh lakh chanderi'', reportedly with complex choreography.<ref name=\"Ranade2006\">{{cite book|author=Ashok Damodar Ranade|title=Hindi Film Song: Music Beyond Boundaries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZI1wqkWsIjYC&pg=PA166|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Bibliophile South Asia|isbn=978-81-85002-64-4|pages=166\u2013}}</ref> He played the lead role of Sant Savata Mali in the movie ''Bhakticha Mala'' released by Rajkamal Kalamandir. He composed the music for this movie and also sang his own songs in this movie. Many aspiring composers of that period - [[Vasant Desai]], C.Ramchandra, [[Sudhir Phadke]], [[Purushottam Laxman Deshpande]], [[Snehal Bhatkar]] and Gajananrao Watve got inspired by his school of musical thought.<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" />\n\n== Honors and later years ==\nPhulambrikar received the Vishnudas Bhave Gold Medal of the Government of Maharashtra in 1969<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" /> and the Government of India awarded him the civilian honor of the [[Padma Bhushan]] in 1971.<ref name=\"Padma Awards\" /> He was the first recipient of the Balgandharv Gold Medal. The [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]] honored him with the [[List of Sangeet Natak Akademi fellows|Sangeet Natak Akademi Ratna Puraskar]] in 1972.<ref name=\"Sangeet Natak Akademi Fellowship\" /> In 1968, he suffered a facial paralysis which forced him to abandon his career as a singer.<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" /> On his 60th career anniversary, a 9-day long music conference was staged in [[Pune]] in which many notable musicians took part.<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" /> He did not survive much longer and the death came on 20 October 1974, when he was 76 years of age.<ref name=\"Ranade2006(2)\">{{cite book|author=Ashok Damodar Ranade|title=Hindi Film Song: Music Beyond Boundaries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZI1wqkWsIjYC&pg=PA163|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Bibliophile South Asia|isbn=978-81-85002-64-4|pages=163\u2013}}</ref> The story of his life has been documented in his biography, ''Bola Amrit Bola'' which was published posthumously in 1985.<ref name=\"Agra gharana & areas of Impact\" /> Every two years an award in his memory is presented to a music critic or author of music book by Maharashtra Sahitya Parishad, Pune. Since his family is originated from Phulambri in Marathwada, a drama theatre has been named \"Master Krishnarao Phulambrikar Natyagruha\" in Jalna, Marathwada in his honour. Every year Pune Bharat Gayan Samaj celebrates his birth anniversary and death anniversary. His daughter, Veena Chitko, who died in September 2015, was a notable light classical musician.<ref name=\"Musical Nite in memory of late Usha Ghosh\">{{cite web | url=http://www.afternoondc.in/culture/musical-nite-in-memory-of-late-usha-ghosh/article_149309 | title=Musical Nite in memory of late Usha Ghosh | publisher=Afternoon Despatch and Courier | date=22 September 2015 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:13%\" | Film\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:5%\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:23%\" | Director\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:17%\" | Producer\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:42%\" | Additional info\n|-\n|[[Dharmatma (1935 film)|Dharmatma]]||1935 ||[[V. Shantaram]] || [[Prabhat Film Company]] ||Originally titles Mahatma\n|-\n|[[Amar Jyoti]]||1936 ||[[V. Shantaram]] || [[Prabhat Film Company]] || [[Shanta Apte]] ,who sang 3 songs, also acted in the film\n|-\n|Wahan||1937 ||K. Narayan Kale || [[Prabhat Film Company]] || [[Shanta Apte]] acted and sang in the film\n|-\n|[[Gopal Krishna (1938 film)|Gopal Krishna]]||1938 ||[[Vishnupant Govind Damle]], Sheikh Fattelal ||  [[Prabhat Film Company]] || Remake of [[Gopal Krishna (1929 film)|1929 silent film]] of the same name\n|-\n|[[Manoos]]||1939 ||[[V. Shantaram]] || [[Prabhat Film Company]] || [[Anil Biswas (composer)|Anil Biswas]] assisted in music composing\n|-\n|[[Aadmi (1939 film)|Aadmi]] ||1939 ||[[V. Shantaram]] || [[Prabhat Film Company]] || Remake of [[Manoos]]\n|-\n|[[Padosi (film)|Padosi]] ||1941 ||[[V. Shantaram]] ||  [[Prabhat Film Company]]||Bilingual in Hindi and Marathi, in Marathi the name was ''Shejari''\n|-\n|Lakharani||1945 ||[[Vishram Bedekar]] ||  [[Prabhat Film Company]] || [[Durga Khote]] starrer\n|-\n|[[Vasantsena (1942 film)|Vasantasena]]||1942 ||[[Gajanan Jagirdar]] || [[Prabhat Film Company]] || Film won the [[National Film Awards|National award]] for second best Marathi film<ref name=\"9thaward\">{{cite web|url=http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm9thNFAAward.aspx|title=9th National Film Awards|publisher=[[International Film Festival of India]]|accessdate=16 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202115652/http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm9thNFAAward.aspx|archive-date=2 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|Bhakticha Mala ||1944 ||[[Keshavrao Date]] || [[Prabhat Film Company]] ||Bilingual (Mali in Marathi), Krishnarao played the lead role\n|-\n|Meri Amanat||1947 ||[[Prabhakar Gupte]] and Shreekant Sutar ||Vikas Picture || Krishnarao acted and sang in the film,music composed by Shridhar Parsekar<ref name=\"Indian films and posters from 1930\">{{cite web | url=https://bombaymann2.blogspot.ae/2014/02/film-meri-amaanat1947.html | title=Indian films and posters from 1930 | publisher=Bombay Mann | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|Sant Ramdas||1949 ||Raja Nene || ||Devotional film\n|-\n|Keechak Vadh||1959 ||Tara Harish and Yashwant Pethkar ||Manik Studios ||[[Lata Mangeshkar]] sang a duet with [[Mohammed Rafi]] and three solos in the film<ref name=\"Keechak Vadh\">{{cite web | url=http://www.hindigeetmala.net/movie/keechak_vadh.htm | title=Keechak Vadh | publisher=Hindi Geet Mala | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|Vithu Majha Lekurwala||1962 ||Datta Dharmadhikari ||Manik Studios ||[[Asha Bhonsle]] sang a song in the film<ref name=\"Marathi Songs's Lyrics\">{{cite web | url=http://geetmanjusha.com/lyrics/12496-vithu-maza-lekurwala-%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%A0%E0%A5%82-%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%9D%E0%A4%BE-%E0%A4%B2%E0%A5%87%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%B3%E0%A4%BE | title=Marathi Songs's Lyrics | publisher=Geet Manjusha | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|Tai Telin||1967 || ||Aryan Film Company ||A biopic about [[Tai Telin]]\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Bal Gandharva]]\n* [[Bhaskarbuwa Bakhale]]\n* [[List of Marathi people]]\n{{div col end}}\n{{portal|India|Music|Film}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.worldcat.org/identities/np-krishnarao%20phulambrikar,%20master$1891%201974/ | title=Krishnarao Phulambrikar, Master | publisher=WorldCat | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.ulhaskashalkar.com/#!gurus/zar5q | title=Nagesh Dattatreya Kashalkar | publisher=Ulhas Kashalkar | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}\n* {{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0471495/?ref_=ttfc_fc_cr2 | title=Master Krishnarao | publisher=Internet Movie Database | work=Profile | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}\n\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 1970\u201379}}\n{{SangeetNatakAkademiFellowship}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Phulambrikar, Krishnarao}}\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in arts]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Sangeet Natak Akademi Fellowship]]\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1974 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Pune district]]\n[[Category:Marathi people]]\n[[Category:Hindi film score composers]]\n[[Category:Indian male classical singers]]\n[[Category:Indian classical composers]]\n[[Category:Indian male composers]]\n[[Category:Marathi-language singers]]\n[[Category:Indian film score composers]]\n[[Category:Hindustani singers]]\n[[Category:Hindustani composers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:19th-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Krishnarao Phulambrikar\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = 20 January 1898\n| birth_place        = [[Alandi|Devachi Alandi]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n| death_date         = {{Death date|df=yes|1974|10|20}}\n| death_place        = Pune\n| restingplace       = \n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| othername          = Master Krishnarao, Master Krishna\n| occupation         = Classical musician<br>Vocalist, Film and Drama artist\n| yearsactive        = \n| known for          = [[Hindustani music]]<br>[[Marathi Sangeet Natak]]<br>[[Marathi and Hindi cinema|Marathi and Hindi film]] music\n| spouse             = Radhabai Phulambrikar\n| domesticpartner    = \n| children           = Madhav alias Raja Phulambrikar, Veena Chitko and Anupama Subhedar\n| parents            = Ganesh Phulambrikar<br>Mathura\n| website            = \n| signature          = \n| awards             = [[Padma Bhushan]]<br>[[List of Sangeet Natak Akademi fellows|Sangeet Natak Akademi Fellowship]]<br>Vishnudas Bhave Gold Medal\n}}\n'''Krishnarao Ganesh Phulambrikar''' (1898\u20131974), popularly known as '''Master Krishnarao''', was an Indian vocalist, classical musician and composer of [[Hindustani music]].<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar\">{{cite web | url=http://www.parrikar.org/vpl/?page_id=672 | title=Krishnarao Phulambrikar | publisher=Vijaya Parrikar Library | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> He was credited with the creation of three Hindustani [[ragas]] and several [[bandish]]es. Phulambrikar, a recipient of the [[List of Sangeet Natak Akademi fellows|Sangeet Natak Akademi Fellowship]],<ref name=\"Sangeet Natak Akademi Fellowship\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/Fellows.html | title=Sangeet Natak Akademi Fellowship | publisher=Sangeet Natak Akademi | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727131515/http://www.sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/Fellows.html | archive-date=27 July 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref> was also the music composer of several movies, including [[Dharmatma (1935 film)|Dharmatma]], a 1935 Hindi film starring [[Bal Gandharva]], a renowned [[Marathi cinema|Marathi]] singer<ref name=\"Dharmatma on IMDb\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0267425/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm | title=Dharmatma on IMDb | publisher=IMDb | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> and [[Padosi (film)|Padosi]], a 1941 directorial venture of [[V. Shantaram]].<ref name=\"Padosi on IMDb\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0331308/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm | title=Padosi on IMDb | publisher=IMDb | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> The Government of India awarded him the third highest civilian honour of the [[Padma Bhushan]], in 1971, for his contributions to music.<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2016 |accessdate=3 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nKrishnarao Phulambrikar was born in 1898 at [[Alandi|Devachi Alandi]], a town in the periphery of [[Pune]], in the western Indian state of [[Maharashtra]] to the [[Deshastha Brahmin]] couple Ganesh Phulambrikar and Mathura bai.<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\">{{cite web | url=https://www.swarganga.org/artist_details.php?id=108 | title=Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas' | publisher=Swar Ganga Music Foundation | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> He also ventured into [[Marathi theatre]] as a child artist by performing as an actor-singer in ''Sant Sakhu'', a musical drama produced by ''Natyakalapravartak Mandali''. He also acted in other musical dramas produced by this drama company. And at this drama company, he first got a chance to learn Indian classical music from Sawai Gandharva who used to act in the musical dramas of this company. Later, he approached the renowned singer, [[Bhaskarbuwa Bakhale]] in 1911 who trained the young boy in [[Gwalior gharana|Gwalior]], [[Agra gharana|Agra]] and [[Jaipur Gharana Lineage|Jaipur]] [[gharanas]] of [[Hindustani music]] and their guru-shishya relationship lasted till Bakhale's death in 1922.<ref name=\"Deodhar1993\">{{cite book|author=B. R. Deodhar|title=Pillars of Hindustani music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cAkUAQAAIAAJ|date=1 October 1993|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7154-555-1}}</ref> The tutelage under Bakhale also gave him opportunity to meet and get associated with [[Bal Gandharva]], who would later go on to become a noted [[Marathi cinema|Marathi singer]].<ref name=\"1898 \u2013 1974 Master Krishnaji Prabhakar Khadilkar\">{{cite web | url=https://fb1site.wordpress.com/2015/11/23/1898-1974-master-krishnaji-prabhakar-khadilkar/ | title=1898 \u2013 1974 Master Krishnaji Prabhakar Khadilkar | publisher=FB1 | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> His first solo concert was when he was 14 years of age (he was awarded the title of ''Sangeet Kalanidhi'' in 1933 by Shankaracharya), which preceded several concerts in India and abroad, including a trip to China as a Government of India delegate in 1953.<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" />\n\nPhulambrikar served as the director of ''Pune Bharat Gayan Samaj'', a music academy founded by his mentor [[Bhaskarbuwa Bakhale]] in Pune.<ref name=\"The Pillars & Mentors\">{{cite web | url=http://www.punebharatgayansamaj.org/history.html | title=The Pillars & Mentors | publisher=Pune Bharat Gayan Samaj | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> Besides his career as a classical vocalist and as a film music composer, he scored music for several plays which included ''Menaka'', ''Savitri'', \"Asha Nirasha\", ''Amritasidhhi'', ''Kanhopatra'', ''Nand Kumar'' and ''Vidhi Likhit'' for ''Gandharva Sangeet Natak Mandali'', a drama company founded by [[Bal Gandharva]], during the period 1915\u20131933 and acted in a few of them. Later, he also composed music for a few plays such as ''Kulavadhu'', ''Ek Hota Mhatara'', ''Kone Eke Kali'' and ''Bhagyoday'' for [[Jyotsna Bhole]].<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" /> On the academic front, he compiled the compositions taught to him by Bakhale as well as his own compositions and published them as a 7-volume book, ''Raag Samgraha''.<ref name=\"Books on Indian Classical Music\">{{cite web | url=https://www.swarganga.org/books.php | title=Books on Indian Classical Music | publisher=Swar Ganga Music Foundation | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Master Krishnarao (1897- )\">{{cite web | url=http://www.moutal.eu/audio-archives/vocal/h-m/289-master-krishnarao-1897-.html | title=Master Krishnarao (1897- ) | publisher=Moutal | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> Besides his notations are available in print under the titles, ''Rashtra Sangeet'', ''Shishu Sangeet'', ''Amar Sangeet'', ''Mohan Maal'', ''Natya Geet Notations'' and ''Chitra Geet Notations''. He also tutored several musicians, film and drama artists. [[Ram Marathe]], Yogini Joglekar, Saraswati Rane, Haribhau Deshpande, Anjanibai Kalgutkar, Madhusudan Kanetkar, Jaymala Shiledar, Dr.Pabalkar, Bapurao Ashtekar, Dattopant Bhope, Pitre buwa, Suhas Datar, Sudhakar Joshi, Ravindra Joshi, Mohan Karve, Rangnath Karkare, Shivram Gadgil and his daughter, Veena Chitko are some of his notable disciples.<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" />\n\n== Hindustani music career ==\nPhulambrikar was known to have had expertise in [[khayal]] and [[Thumri]] traditions of classical music rendition and was aligned to the [[Agra gharana]].<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" /> He created several [[ragas]] by merging the nuances of different ragas; thus he created ''Tilak Kedar'' based on Tilak Kamod and Kedar ragas, Mangal Todi on [[Todi (raga)|Todi]] and Madhyam, Shiva Kalyan on [[Kalyani (raga)|Kalyan]] and [[Shivaranjani]], Bilvabibhas on [[Bilaval]] and [[Bibhas]] and Jaunkali based on [[Jaunpuri (raga)|Jaunpuri]] and [[Ramkali]] ragas. He was reported to have initiated the practice of creating new Natyapadas<ref name=\"Agra gharana & areas of Impact\">{{cite web | url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/56174/12/12_chapter%205.pdf | title=Agra gharana & areas of Impact | publisher=Shodh Ganga | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> and composed many [[bandish]]es such as ''Ratiya Mein Jagi'' ([[Kanada (raga group)|Rag Nayaki Kanada]]), ''Lalan Tumabina Kaun'' ([[Kanada (raga group)|Rag Kaunsi Kanada]]), ''Rang Rang Mukhape'' ([[Adana (raga)|Rag Adana]]), ''Chahu Barasan Lagi'' ([[Bhopali|Rag Bhopali]]), ''Kahu Ki Reet'' ([[Malkaush|Rag Malkaush]]), ''Hori Khela! Bahar'' ([[Patdeep|Rag Patdeep]]), ''E Ma Badal Aye'' ([[Malhar|Rag Malhar]]), Mai Ri Aaj ([[Hindol|Rag Hindol Bahar]]), Mai Pritam Karo Dulhan Pe ([[Kalyani (raga)|Rag Shiv Kalyan]]).<ref name=\"The raags of the Ganesh pandals: The magic of Master Krishnarao\">{{cite web | url=http://scroll.in/article/755954/the-raags-of-the-ganesh-pandals-the-magic-of-master-krishnarao | title=The raags of the Ganesh pandals: The magic of Master Krishnarao | publisher=Scroll.in | date=19 September 2015 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> ''Tori Binati'', ''Dekho Mori Churiya'', ''Shamamohan Pyare'', ''Khelat Hai Giridhari'', ''Ho Sham Bajayetore Gharame Muraliya'', all in [[Bhairavi (raga)|Rag Bhairavi]], were some of his notable thumris in Bhairavi, earning him the sobriquet, ''Bhairavi ke Badshah'' and the style he developed came to be known as ''Khayali Thumri'' or ''Madhyamgram Thumri''.<ref name=\"Regional Varieties of Thumri\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nadsadhna.com/Pages/IndianMusic/Gharanas.asp?About=Baneras | title=Regional Varieties of Thumri | publisher=Nad Sadhna | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> He tuned the Indian national song, [[Vande Mataram]],  in ''Raag Jhinjhoti'' and tried unsuccessfully to promote the song as the [[National Anthem of India|national anthem]].<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" /> On special request made by Dr.Babasaheb Ambedkar, he composed music for Buddha Vandana.\n\n== Film career ==\nSoon after he received the Sangeet Kalanidhi title from Dr. Kurtkoti, the Shankaracharya of Karvir Peeth, he was contracted by [[Prabhat Film Company]]<ref name=\"The Talkie Era \">{{cite web | url=https://www.cs.colostate.edu/~malaiya/music_hist.html | title=The Talkie Era | publisher=Colostate | date=2016 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> owned by [[V. Shantaram]] and other partners,<ref name=\"GokulsingDissanayake2013\">{{cite book|author1=K. Moti Gokulsing|author2=Wimal Dissanayake|title=Routledge Handbook of Indian Cinemas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=djUFmlFbzFkC&pg=PA259|date=17 April 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-77284-9|pages=259\u2013}}</ref> to compose music for its forthcoming film, [[Dharmatma (1935 film)|Dharmatma]], where he was re-united with his old associate, [[Bal Gandharva]], who played the role of [[Sant Eknath]], the protagonist of the movie.<ref name=\"Full Cast & Crew\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0267425/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm | title=Full Cast & Crew | publisher=IMDb | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> The film which was released in 1935 had sixteen songs, many of them sung by Bal Gandharva.<ref name=\"Dharmatma Songs\">{{cite web | url=http://muvyz.com/moviepage/es289902/songs/#tabs | title=Dharmatma Songs | publisher=Muvyz | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> A year later, his next film was released under the name, [[Amar Jyoti]], again a Prabhat Film Company production.<ref name=\"Amar Jyoti (1936)\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0268915/?ref_=nm_flmg_com_7 | title=Amar Jyoti (1936) | publisher=IMDb | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> The film was reported to have been critically acclaimed and was the first Indian film to be screened at the [[Venice Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Rishi2012\">{{cite book|author=Tilak Rishi|title=Bless You Bollywood!: A Tribute to Hindi Cinema on Completing 100 Years|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r623sWyGm0sC&pg=PA155|year=2012|publisher=Trafford Publishing|isbn=978-1-4669-3963-9|pages=155\u2013}}</ref> ''Wahan'', another Prabhat production released in 1937, this time with a new director, K. Narayan Kale, was his next film,<ref name=\"Wahan (1937)\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0232919/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm | title=Wahan (1937) | publisher=IMDb | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> followed by the musical [[Gopal Krishna (1938 film)|Gopal Krishna]] in 1938 directed by Damle and S Fattelal.<ref name=\"Gopal Krishna (1938)\">{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0158642/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm | title=Gopal Krishna (1938) | publisher=IMDb | date=2016 | accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> He composed music for 15 films which included [[Padosi (film)|Padosi]], another Shantaram film and the film featured a ten-minute song, ''Lakh lakh chanderi'', reportedly with complex choreography.<ref name=\"Ranade2006\">{{cite book|author=Ashok Damodar Ranade|title=Hindi Film Song: Music Beyond Boundaries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZI1wqkWsIjYC&pg=PA166|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Bibliophile South Asia|isbn=978-81-85002-64-4|pages=166\u2013}}</ref> He played the lead role of Sant Savata Mali in the movie ''Bhakticha Mala'' released by Rajkamal Kalamandir. He composed the music for this movie and also sang his own songs in this movie. Many aspiring composers of that period - [[Vasant Desai]], C.Ramchandra, [[Sudhir Phadke]], [[Purushottam Laxman Deshpande]], [[Snehal Bhatkar]] and Gajananrao Watve got inspired by his school of musical thought.<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" />\n\n== Honors and later years ==\nPhulambrikar received the Vishnudas Bhave Gold Medal of the Government of Maharashtra in 1969<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" /> and the Government of India awarded him the civilian honor of the [[Padma Bhushan]] in 1971.<ref name=\"Padma Awards\" /> He was the recipient of the Balgandharv Gold Medal. The [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]] honored him with the [[List of Sangeet Natak Akademi fellows|Sangeet Natak Akademi Ratna Puraskar]] in 1972.<ref name=\"Sangeet Natak Akademi Fellowship\" /> In 1968, he suffered a facial paralysis which forced him to abandon his career as a singer.<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" /> On his 60th career anniversary, a 9-day long music conference was staged in [[Pune]] in which many notable musicians took part.<ref name=\"Krishnarao Phulambrikar 'Krishnadas'\" /> He did not survive much longer and the death came on 20 October 1974, when he was 76 years of age.<ref name=\"Ranade2006(2)\">{{cite book|author=Ashok Damodar Ranade|title=Hindi Film Song: Music Beyond Boundaries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZI1wqkWsIjYC&pg=PA163|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Bibliophile South Asia|isbn=978-81-85002-64-4|pages=163\u2013}}</ref> The story of his life has been documented in his biography, ''Bola Amrit Bola'' which was published posthumously in 1985.<ref name=\"Agra gharana & areas of Impact\" /> Every two years an award in his memory is presented to a music critic or author of music book by Maharashtra Sahitya Parishad, Pune. Since his family is originated from Phulambri in Marathwada, a drama theatre has been named \"Master Krishnarao Phulambrikar Natyagruha\" in Jalna, Marathwada in his honour. Every year Pune Bharat Gayan Samaj celebrates his birth anniversary and death anniversary. His daughter, Veena Chitko, who died in September 2015, was a notable light classical musician.<ref name=\"Musical Nite in memory of late Usha Ghosh\">{{cite web | url=http://www.afternoondc.in/culture/musical-nite-in-memory-of-late-usha-ghosh/article_149309 | title=Musical Nite in memory of late Usha Ghosh | publisher=Afternoon Despatch and Courier | date=22 September 2015 | accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{